NAME: Casa Loma
ATTRACTION Description: Canadas foremost castle is complete with decorated suites, secret passages, an 800-foot tunnel, towers, stables, and beautiful 5-acre estate gardens.

NAME: CN Tower
ATTRACTION Description: The CN Tower is an engineering marvel and one of the city's most visited sites. It features the world's highest wine cellar, a fine dining revolving restaurant (360), a glass floor. For the true adventure seeker, the Edge walk.

NAME: Hockey Hall of Fame
ATTRACTION Description: Unique to Toronto, and featuring the Stanley Cup, interactive exhibits, shows, and the finest collection of hockey artifacts in the world.

NAME: Polson Pier
ATTRACTION Description: Located on the water, the Polson Pier is a waterfront property that includes a drive-in cinema, patio bar, concert venues, and much more.

NAME: Ripley's Aquarium of Canada
ATTRACTION Description: Canadas largest aquarium. Interactive attractions feature over 5.7 million litres of water and more than 16,000 marine animals.

NAME: Riverdale Farm
ATTRACTION Description: On 7.5 acres, Riverdale Farm is an historic working farm with many scenic pathways and farm animals.

NAME: St. Lawrence Market and Market Gallery
ATTRACTION Description: Voted best fresh food market in the world by National Geographic in 2012, Torontos historic and premier market also includes The Market Gallery, housed within part of Torontos original 19th century City Hall.

NAME: The Distillery Historic District
ATTRACTION Description: A collection of boutiques, galleries, cafes and restaurants takes the place of a former distillery.

NAME: Toronto Sign
ATTRACTION Description: 10 foot tall, light up letters that spell Toronto set against a city-skyline backdrop.

NAME: Cineplex Cinemas Varsity and VIP
ATTRACTION Description: Modern multiplex cinema chain screening the latest Hollywood films, plus new independent releases.

NAME: Cineplex Cinemas Yonge-Dundas and VIP
ATTRACTION Description: Modern multiplex cinema chain screening the latest Hollywood films, plus new independent releases.

NAME: Imagine Cinemas Carlton Cinema
ATTRACTION Description: The Carlton Cinema is a cinema in Toronto, Ontario, Canada. It is located on Carlton Street on the original premises of the historic Odeon Theatre and is known for playing films that the larger chain theatres ignore.

NAME: Imagine Cinemas Market Square
ATTRACTION Description: Modern multiplex cinema chain screening the latest Hollywood films, plus new independent releases.

NAME: Scotiabank Theatre Toronto
ATTRACTION Description: The Scotiabank Theatre Toronto is a major movie theatre at the RioCan Hall in the Entertainment District of downtown Toronto, Ontario, Canada at Richmond and John Street owned by Cineplex Entertainment for the building and the lands owned by RioCan.

NAME: The Royal Cinema
ATTRACTION Description: The Royal Cinema is an Art Moderne event venue and cinema in Toronto, Ontario, Canada. It was built in 1939 and owned by Miss Ray Levinsky. When it was built in 1939, it was called The Pylon, with an accompanying large sign at the front of the theatre

NAME: TIFF Bell Lightbox
ATTRACTION Description: TIFF Bell Lightbox is a cultural centre in Toronto, Ontario, Canada, located in the first five floors of the Bell Lightbox and Festival Tower on the north west corner of King Street and John Street.

NAME: Beanfield Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The Beanfield Centre (formerly Allstream Centre) is an environmentally friendly conference venue.

NAME: Enercare Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The largest convention centre in Canada, over 180 trade and consumer shows are hosted annually.

NAME: Metro Toronto Centre
ATTRACTION Description: Offers more than 600,000 square feet of large exhibit, event, and meeting space.

NAME: Shoppes Of the World Trade Centre
ATTRACTION Description: Amazing collection. Friendly staff. A must visit place. They have good deals time to time

NAME: BMO Field
ATTRACTION Description: BMO Field is home to the Toronto FC (Major League Soccer), Canada's national soccer team, and the home of the Toronto Argonauts (Canadian Football League).

NAME: Budweiser Stage (formerly Molson Canadian Amphitheatre)
ATTRACTION Description: Located within the Ontario Place grounds, the Budweiser Stage offers concert goers an excellent outdoors venue.

NAME: Coca-Cola Coliseum (formerly Ricoh Coliseum)
ATTRACTION Description: Located at Exhibition Place, the Coca-Cola Coliseum is home to the Toronto Marlies (American Hockey League) and concerts.

NAME: Mattamy Athletic Centre
ATTRACTION Description: Mattamy Athletic Centre is located within Maple Leafs Garden and is home to the Ryerson Ram's basketball, hockey and volleyball teams.

NAME: Rogers Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The Rogers Centre is a multipurpose venue. Home to the Toronto Blue Jays (Major League Baseball) and the Toronto Argonauts (Canadian Football League).

NAME: Scotiabank Arena (formerly Air Canada Centre)
ATTRACTION Description: The Scotiabank Arena is a multi-purpose indoor sporting arena and concert venue. It is the home of the Toronto Maple Leafs Hockey Club, the Toronto Raptors basketball team, and the Toronto Rock Lacrosse team.

NAME: Art Gallery of Ontario
ATTRACTION Description: The Art Gallery of Ontario (AGO) is one of the largest art galleries in North America, and holds more than 80,000 works in its collection. In 2008 the building was redesigned by famous architect and native Torontonian, Frank Gehry.

NAME: Art Museum at the University of Toronto
ATTRACTION Description: Originally opened in 1996 The Arts centre puts a special focus on study collections.

NAME: Canadian Sculpture Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The Canadian Scultpture Centre is headquarters to the Sculptors Society of Canada. The society showcases and exibits contemporary Canadian scultpures.

NAME: Gallery Indigena
ATTRACTION Description: Located in the Distillery District, the Eskimo Art Gallery offers Inuit art.

NAME: Museum of Contemporary Canadian Art
ATTRACTION Description: A variety of original and thought-provoking exhibitions, promoting innovative art by Canadian and international artists. Over 800 artists have been featured in more than 80 exhibitions and projects.

NAME: Onsite [at] OCADU
ATTRACTION Description: Onsite [at] OCAD U provides the opportunity and space of an art gallery to exhibit students contemporary work.

NAME: Ryerson Image Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The RIC is dedicated to the public exhibition, research, study and teaching of photography including, installation art and film and media.

NAME: The Power Plant Contemporary Art Gallery
ATTRACTION Description: Dedicated to contemporary art, the Power Plant is a free public gallery located at the Harbourfront Centre.

NAME: Thompson Landry Gallery - Stone Building & Cooperage Space
ATTRACTION Description: The Thompson Landry Gallery is spread out over 6,000 square feet and showcases artwork from internationally acclaimed contemporary Quebec artists. The gallery opened in 2009 and is situated within the Distillery District's Cooperage Building.

NAME: Artscape Wychwood Barns
ATTRACTION Description: A heritage building converted into a community centre that hosts many events, festivals, farmers market and a children's theatre.

NAME: Canada's Walk of Fame
ATTRACTION Description: Canada's Walk of Fame celebrates Canadians who have excelled in their respective fields for at least 10 years. The stars are displayed throughout the Entertainment District along King Street West and Simcoe Street.

NAME: CF Toronto Eaton Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The Toronto Eaton Centre is downtown Toronto's only shopping mall. It features over 200 stores and restaurants as well as the sculpture called Flightstop designed by Michael Snow.

NAME: Louie Laki Lane
ATTRACTION Description: Louie Laki worked in a foundry and enjoyed a glass of homemade wine.

NAME: MacMillian Co. of Canada Building
ATTRACTION Description: Historical landmark

NAME: MuchMusic (Bell Media Queen Street)
ATTRACTION Description: A Canadian television channel dedicated to engaging the youth through popular music and popular television series.

NAME: Old City Hall
ATTRACTION Description: Old City Hall is a landmark building that was used as Toronto's second City Hall and is a great example of beautiful architecture. Today, it is used as a courthouse.

NAME: Osgoode Hall
ATTRACTION Description: Constructed in the 19th century, Osgoode Hall acts as the judicial landmark of Toronto, with institutions like the Ontario Court of Appeal, the Law Society of Upper Canada, and the Divisional Court of the Superior Court of Justice.

NAME: Queen's Park: Legislative Assembly of Ontario
ATTRACTION Description: A variety of free tour options are available all year round to visit Ontarios historic Legislative Building (iconic sandstone Richardson Romanesque style building, completed in 1893).

NAME: Redrocket Lane
ATTRACTION Description: A pedestrian only historic area that represents the largest and best preserved collection of Victorian Industrial Architecture in North America. The refurbished warehouses are now home to restaurants, bars, galleries, studios, and a theatre.

NAME: Tony Brady Lane
ATTRACTION Description: Famously known as being North America's oldest company, the Hudson Bay is a chain of department stores  that operate throughout the country.

NAME: Toronto City Hall and Nathan Phillips Square
ATTRACTION Description: Toronto's City Hall is one of Toronto's best known and visited landmarks. Nathan Phillips Square located directly in front of City Hall, is the site of  the iconic Toronto sign, concerts, farmers' markets, and iconic events.

NAME: Toronto Public Labyrinth at Trinity Square
ATTRACTION Description: Trinity Square Park offers a unique age-old experience of meditating and relaxing while walking a labyrinth and focusing on personal self-awareness and spiritual growth.

NAME: Toronto Reference Library
ATTRACTION Description: The Toronto Reference Library is situated in a 5 storey building within the Yorkville neighbourhood. It is the largest public reference library in Canada.

NAME: Yonge-Dundas Square
ATTRACTION Description: Yonge-Dundas Square is one of the city's largest public squares. It is located directly across from the Toronto Eaton Centre. The square is home to free movie screenings, concerts, shows and exhibits.

NAME: CBC Museum
ATTRACTION Description: The CBC Museum features various CBC archival materials that date back to 1936. The museum also features the Graham Spry Theatre and a number of interactive exhibits.

NAME: Colborne Lodge
ATTRACTION Description: This quaint cottage located within High Park was home to John and Jemma Howard. In 1873 the couple deeded the part to lodge to the City of Toronto. The house is a great example of a regency style building.

NAME: Design Exchange
ATTRACTION Description: Canada's only museum dedicated to the preservation of design which includes the design heritage from an array of mediums.

NAME: Fort York National Historic Site
ATTRACTION Description: Birthplace of Toronto in 1793 and scene of the Battle of York in 1813, Fort York has Canadas largest collection of original War of 1812 buildings. Open year round for tours, exhibits, and demonstrations.

NAME: Gardiner Museum of Ceramic Art
ATTRACTION Description: A museum dedicated to one of the oldest forms of art. The Gardiner Museum of Ceramic Art is home to over 3,000 historical and contemporary ceramic pieces.

NAME: Japan Foundation
ATTRACTION Description: A cultural establishment aiming towards effective development of its international cultural exchange programs in Japanese arts and cultural exchange.

NAME: Mackenzie House
ATTRACTION Description: Mackenzie House is the restored home of William Lyon Mackenzie, Toronto's first Mayor. It is one of 10 museums operated by the City of Toronto.

NAME: Redpath Sugar Museum
ATTRACTION Description: Located inside the Redpath Refinery, the Redpath Sugar Museum is for those interested in the history of sugar, the development and the role of the Redpath family in Canada's industry sector, and much more.

NAME: Reuben & Helene Dennis Museum
ATTRACTION Description: The Toronto Railway Museum encompasses the Canadian Pacific Railway John Street Roundhouse at Roundhouse Park and features a restored turntable, a number of trains and the 1896 Canadian Pacific Don Station.

NAME: Royal Ontario Museum
ATTRACTION Description: Canadas largest museum of natural history and world cultures, presents engaging galleries of art, archaeology, and natural science from around the world.

NAME: Spadina Museum
ATTRACTION Description: Operated by the City of Toronto, the Spadina Museum is a historic manor house that allows visitors to learn about the history and architecture of  late 19th century to early 20th century Toronto.

NAME: Taras H. Shevchenko Museum
ATTRACTION Description: The Taras H. Shevchenko Museum is the home to  exhibitions dedicated to the contribution of Ukrainians in Canada and the life of famed writer Taras Shevchenko.

NAME: Textile Museum of Canada
ATTRACTION Description: With more than 13,000 objects from more than 200 countries and regions, the Textile Museum of Canada celebrates cultural diversity through traditional fabrics, garments, carpets and related artifacts such as beadwork and basketry.

NAME: The 48th Highlanders Museum
ATTRACTION Description: This museum is dedicated to one of Canada's famous military regiments. The museum holds historical artifacts dating from Victorian Toronto in 1891, when the 48th Highlanders was formed, to the present day.

NAME: The Bata Shoe Museum
ATTRACTION Description: Home to hundreds of shoes (from a collection numbering over 13,000). The museum celebrates the style and function of footwear in impressive galleries from ancient Egypt to modern fashion.

NAME: Toronto Police Museum & Discovery Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The Toronto Police Museum & Discovery Centre occupies 3,000 square feet within the Police Headquarters building on College Street. The museum solely relies on private donations and is a not for profit registered charity.

NAME: Toronto's First Post Office
ATTRACTION Description: Toronto's First Post Office acts as a museum but also continues to operate as a full service Canada Post office. Admission to the museum is by donation.

NAME: Ukrainian Museum of Canada
ATTRACTION Description: The Ukrainian Museum of Canada features over 4,000 artifacts. These artifacts include prints, coins, maps jewellery, textiles and historic costumes.

NAME: Cloud Gardens Conservatory
ATTRACTION Description: Renovated in 2014, the conservatory is situated within the heart of the city's financial district. It features a small greenhouse that is set to the conditions of a rainforest.

NAME: Glen Stewart Park
ATTRACTION Description: The garden, inspired by Franklin the Turtle, is an area to discover nature, play, while learning something new.

NAME: Alexander Muir Memorial Gardens
ATTRACTION Description: Named after the famous composer Alexander Muir. The gardens act as a path into the tranquil ravine system that includes walking trails. The gardens are open year round.

NAME: Allan Gardens
ATTRACTION Description: Allan Gardens is a park and indoor botanical garden built in 1910. The building houses six greenhouses featuring plants and flowers from across the globe. Open year round and free to the public.

NAME: Balmy Beach Park
ATTRACTION Description: Created in 1903, the historic park features a lawn bowling club, a playground and outdoor fitness equipment.

NAME: Cherry Beach/ Clarke Beach Park
ATTRACTION Description: Cherry Beach is located within the port lands and features a dog's off leash area, the Martin Goodman Trail and a picnic site.

NAME: Chorley Park
ATTRACTION Description: A quiet 5 hectare park near Mount Pleasant Road and St. Clair Avenue East featuring a mature tree canopy and picnic tables.

NAME: Etienne Brule Park
ATTRACTION Description: Etienne Brule park is a historically significant piece of land. It was named after Etienne Brule, the first French explorer to venture beyond the St. Lawrence River into Upper Canada

NAME: Bellevue Square Park
ATTRACTION Description: Measuring just under half a hectare, Bellevue Square is a small park in the heart of Toronto's Kensington Market neighbourhood. This park features a wading pool, playground and drinking fountain. It is also home to a life size bronze statue of Toronto-born actor and director Al Waxman, best known for his role as Larry King in the television series King of Kensington.

NAME: High Park
ATTRACTION Description: High Park is one of Torontos largest parks, and attracts visitors each spring for the blooming of its famous cherry blossoms. It also contains attractions and amenities such as recreational programs, a local zoo, a unique playground and a pond.

NAME: HTO Park
ATTRACTION Description: Facing the inner harbour with Toronto Island Park in clear viewing,  HTO Park includes an urban beach which is decorated with yellow umbrellas and Muskoka chairs.

NAME: Kew Gardens Park
ATTRACTION Description: Located in The Beaches, Kew Gardens act as one of Toronto's most popular picnic grounds while having access to the boardwalk on the lakeshore.

NAME: Riverdale Park (East and West)
ATTRACTION Description: A Toronto park that is great for all seasons. Riverdale Park West has three multipurpose sport fields, seven tennis courts, an outdoor ice rink, two baseball diamonds, and much more.

NAME: S.A.D.R.A. Park
ATTRACTION Description: S.A.D.R.A Park is a small park with a playground and ball hockey pad. S.A.D.R.A.

NAME: St. James Park
ATTRACTION Description: A large green space, home to a Victorian garden, live performances, and is a popular spot for photos. The park is adjacent to historic St. James Cathedral.

NAME: Sugar Beach Park
ATTRACTION Description: Sugar Beach is one of Toronto's urban beach parks. Famous for its pink umbrellas and Muskoka chairs.

NAME: Sunnyside Beach
ATTRACTION Description: One of Toronto's designated swimming beaches, Sunnyside Beach provides rowers and paddlers calm waters with an offshore break wall.

NAME: Taddle Creek Park
ATTRACTION Description: Compact city green space featuring a playground for kids and a pitcher-shaped fountain sculpture

NAME: Tommy Thompson Park
ATTRACTION Description: This narrow peninsula park is a perfect place for hiking, jogging, cycling and birdwatching, with 10km of paved trails.

NAME: Toronto Music Garden
ATTRACTION Description: The Toronto Music Garden is situated on Toronto's newly revamped waterfront. The garden was designed by landscape designer Julie Moir Messervy and by the cellist Yo Yo Ma.

NAME: Toronto Sculpture Garden
ATTRACTION Description: Since 1981 this small urban park has featured contemporary sculpture installations by various artists.

NAME: Village of Yorkville Park
ATTRACTION Description: The Village of Yorkville Park was built on the site of a former parking lot, in the heart of the Bloor Yorkville neighbourhood. The main focal point of the park is the rock which weighs 650 tonnes and is approximately 1 billion years old.

NAME: Dufferin Grove Park
ATTRACTION Description: Dufferin Grove Park is a park in the Dufferin Grove neighbourhood of Toronto, Ontario, Canada. The park is located on the east side of Dufferin Street, south of Bloor Street West.

NAME: Woodbine Beach
ATTRACTION Description: Woodbine Beach is one of the city's main beaches. The park is located over 15.2 hectares.  Features include the Martin Goodman Trail and the Donald D. Summerville Outdoor Olympic Pool.

NAME: Al Green Theatre (at the Miles Nadal Jewish Community Centre)
ATTRACTION Description: The Al Green Theatre is used  for social and corporate event, theatre, film, concerts, dance; and lectures.

NAME: Alumnae Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: The theatre company is housed inside an old firehall and is the oldest theatre society in Toronto. Each year the company offers three productions.

NAME: Berkeley Street Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Home to the Canadian Stage Company, the Berkeley Street Theatre presents an array of Canadian and international performances.

NAME: Betty Oliphant Theatre (at Canada's National Ballet School)
ATTRACTION Description: Designed by Jack Diamond, the Betty Oliphant Theatre is used by the Canada National Ballet School as a training and performance venue.

NAME: Buddies in Bad Times Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Buddies in Bad Times theatre is the biggest, and the longest-running queer theatre in the world.

NAME: CAA Theatre (formerly Panasonic Theatre)
ATTRACTION Description: Owned by Mirvish Productions, the CAA Theatre is the home of many famous theatrical productions.

NAME: Centennial College Theatre Arts and Performance
ATTRACTION Description: Located on the main floor of the Canadian Broadcasting Centre,  the Glenn Gould Studio is a much-celebrated venue for its state of the art recording facilities and acoustics.

NAME: Dancemakers and the Centre for Creation
ATTRACTION Description: One of Toronto's professional contemporary dance companies, Dancemakers and the Centre for Creation is focused on the delivery of refined and passionate dance to its admirers.

NAME: Ed Mirvish Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: A part of the Toronto theatre scene since 1920, the Ed Mirvish Theatre is a picturesque theatre to view special presentations ranging from concerts, comedy, plays, and many more.

NAME: Elgin and Winter Garden Theatre Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The Elgin and Winter Garden Theatre features two completely separate theatres and is the last running double-decker theatre in the world .

NAME: Factory Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: The Factory Theatre operates two theatres in a  Victorian mansion, where they have produced more than 150 Canadian plays, and various workshops.

NAME: Four Seasons Centre for the Performing Arts
ATTRACTION Description: The Four Seasons Centre for the Performing Arts is home to the Canadian Opera Company and the National Ballet of Canada.

NAME: George Ignatieff Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: In the Trinity College community, the George Ignatieff Theatre acts as a creative hub ranging from events like theatre, conferences, and much more.

NAME: Harbourfront Centre
ATTRACTION Description: Popular 10 acre lakeside cultural site offers an eclectic blend of year-round arts, culture and recreation such as concerts, skating, music festivals and dance.

NAME: Hart House Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: A point of interest in the University of Toronto community, the Hart House Theatre and it's students produce an array of drama, dance, film, and music.

NAME: Isabel Bader Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Located at the University of Toronto, this multi-purpose venue seats 500 patrons whether it be for a lecture, workshop, or a theatrical production.

NAME: Kineto Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Red Sky Performance is a 1,135 seat venue to provide excellent acoustic sounds for all genres of music in its shoebox designed venue.

NAME: Lower Ossington Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: A theatrical hub for downtown Toronto's west end, the Lower Ossington Theatre is home to special presentations, rehearsals, and classes.

NAME: Massey Hall
ATTRACTION Description: Declared a heritage building in  the 1970s, this live events venue acts as a performance venue for various artists.

NAME: Medieval Times Dinner and Tournament
ATTRACTION Description: A family dinner theatre featuring staged medieval-style games, sword-fighting, and jousting performed by a cast of actors and horses.

NAME: Meridian Hall (formerly Sony Centre for the Performing Arts)
ATTRACTION Description: Meridian Hall is a performing arts venue with a range of events that include concerts, dance, and much more.

NAME: Mysteriously Yours Mystery Dinner Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Mysteriously Yours. Mystery Dinner Theatre is a murder mystery dinner theatre located in  Downtown Toronto.

NAME: Native Earth Performing Arts and Aki Studio
ATTRACTION Description: Native Earth Performing Arts is a theatre company devoted to the artistic expression of the Indigenous experience. Located in Daniels Spectrum.

NAME: Princess of Wales Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Owned by Mirvish Productions. The Princess of Wales Theatre opened in 1993 and is the home  of many famous theatrical productions

NAME: Queen Elizabeth Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Located at Exhibition Place, the Queen Elizabeth Theatre is an auditorium that is the venue for various entertainment events

NAME: Randolph Centre for the Arts
ATTRACTION Description: The historic Randolph Theatre is a 500-seat theatre located in a former Gothic revival style church.

NAME: Roy Thomson Hall
ATTRACTION Description: Opened in 1982, Roy Thomson Hall is home of the Toronto Symphony Orchestra and the Toronto Mendelssohn Choir.

NAME: Royal Alexandra Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Owned by Mirvish Productions. The Royal Alexandra Theatre built in beaux-arts architectural style in 1907. It is home to numerous performances and performers.

NAME: Ryerson Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Ryerson Theatre is home to various productions which includes concerts, film presentations, and Ryerson Theatre and Fashion Schools productions.

NAME: Solar Stage Children's Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: Solar Stage Children's Theatre is dedicated to providing theatrical presentations for children.

NAME: St. Lawrence Centre for the Arts
ATTRACTION Description: Home to  two theatres, the Bluma Appel Theatre and the Jane Mallett Theatre, the St. Lawrence Centre for the Arts is the home to various artistic and public events.

NAME: Tarragon Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: The Tarragon Theatre is a performing arts centre  notable for the development of playwrights. Over 170 works have premiered at the theatre.

NAME: The Danforth Music Hall
ATTRACTION Description: The Music Hall boasts new theatre seats, state-of-art sound and lighting and a completely renovated backstage area.

NAME: The Gerald Isaac Studio
ATTRACTION Description: The Toronto Conservatory of Music was founded in 1886.

NAME: The Second City
ATTRACTION Description: Second City produces premiere comedy performances and operates a training centre.

NAME: The Theatre Centre
ATTRACTION Description: The Theatre Centre supports artists who wish to develop works of an experimental or alternative nature. All their artists embrace the visual arts, music, dance and new media.

NAME: The Village Playhouse
ATTRACTION Description: The Village Playhouse a non-profit theatre group that opened its doors in 1974 and has since produced plays such as Cat on a Hot Tin Roof, Amadeus and Dial 'M' For Murder.

NAME: Theatre Passe Muraille
ATTRACTION Description: Theatre Passe Muraille was Canadas original alternative theatre company. 600 Canadian plays have been produced since the company was founded in 1968.

NAME: Winchester Street Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: The Winchester Street Theatre is owned and jointly operated by the Toronto Dance Theatre and the School of Toronto Dance Theatre. The venue features rake seating and a stage that best showcases dance performances.

NAME: Young Centre for the Performing Arts
ATTRACTION Description: Opened in 2006 the Young Centre for the Performing Arts has seen more than 250,000 people attend its performances. The theatre is located within the Distillery Historic District.

NAME: Young People's Theatre
ATTRACTION Description: The Young People Theatre is a part of the Soulpepper theatre company located within the Distillery Historic District.

NAME: Yuk Yuk's
ATTRACTION Description: Yuk Yuk's was established as a comedy club by Mark Breslin in 1976. It is located within Toronto's entertainment district and features various comedians doing their stand up routines.

NAME: Adega Restaurante
ATTRACTION Description: Intimate space for seafood and other dishes from Portugal and Spain plus a large Portuguese wine list.

NAME: Byblos Downtown
ATTRACTION Description: Luxe, 2 story restaurant putting a contemporary spin on Eastern Mediterranean cuisine and cocktails.

NAME: Como En Casa
ATTRACTION Description: Tiny Mexican canteen serving tacos, stews, burritos & other substantial dinner plates.

NAME: Lena Restaurante
ATTRACTION Description: Chic South American restaurant featuring elevated lunch & dinner menus, plus cocktails & bar bites.

NAME: RASA
ATTRACTION Description: Global-inspired snacks & entrees in a sleek, dark space from food-truck mavens The Food Dudes.

NAME: Senso Cafe Restaurant
ATTRACTION Description: The journey to having senso restaurant become a reality was long, but the experience needed in every aspect of customer satisfation was the golden result of this journey . At senso, the staff have been trained to serve at cutting edge standards.

NAME: Volos Greek Cuisine
ATTRACTION Description: Upscale Greek cuisine & wines in a refined, contemporary setting, with fixed-price theatre specials.

NAME: Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport
ATTRACTION Description: Located minutes from the downtown core, Billy Bishop Airport serves nearby Canadian and American cities.

NAME: Jack Layton Ferry Terminal
ATTRACTION Description: Located at the foot of Bay Street and Queens Quay West, the  Jack Layton Ferry Terminal acts as a commuting point to and from the Toronto Island Park with frequent ferry service.

NAME: Toronto Coach Terminal
ATTRACTION Description: The Toronto Coach Terminal provides travellers with bus service to various cities in North America.

NAME: Union Station
ATTRACTION Description: Union Station is the busiest transportation hub in all of Canada. It serves more than 250,000 passengers daily. Via Rail, the TTC, Go Transit and Amtrak all operate out of the station

NAME: Attractions Ontario
ATTRACTION Description: Your all-in-one Ontario Tourism site! Find facts on the best things to do in Ontario. We provide you with the most current information

NAME: Tahiti Tourisme - Canada
ATTRACTION Description: They offer free services to the general travelling public.
